  "chunk_index": 15,
  "summary": "While traveling by train, Hercule Poirot and Hastings receive news from Inspector Croome that Sir Clement Clarke has been found dead. Sir Clarke, a renowned throat specialist and Chinese art collector, was discovered on a walking route near his seaside home in Devonshire, having been struck violently on the head. An ABC train timetable was found placed face up on his body. Poirot observes that this is the first instance of a \"non-private\" murder, as the victim was a stranger to the investigators rather than someone close to a previous victim. He suspects the killer's desire for publicity may lead to carelessness.\n\nUpon arriving at Kensington House, the investigators meet the deceased's brother, Franklin Clarke, a resourceful man of action, and the butler, Devereaux. During breakfast, Franklin expresses skepticism regarding the serial killer theory and the lack of a clear motive. Inspector Croome suggests the killer's motive might be to create a sensation and become a public figure. \n\nWhen questioned about his brother's state of mind, Franklin reveals that Sir Clarke was often agitated due to the poor health of his wife, who suffers from incurable cancer. Franklin also mentions that he has recently returned from the East and noticed changes in his brother. In response to a hypothetical question from Poirot regarding a body found with a revolver, Franklin states he would immediately conclude the death was a suicide.",
